DOCUMENT();

loadMacros('PGstandard.pl', 'PGML.pl', 'PGcourse.pl');

Context('Numeric')->variables->are(t => Real);

$a    = random(100000, 300000, 1000);
$year = random(2005,   2020);
$yr2  = random(2025,   2035);
$b    = random(2,      6, 1);
$r    = $b / 100;
$rp1  = 1+$r;
$diff = $yr2 - $year;

$c = int($a * exp($r * $y)) + 1150;

$model = Formula("$a*(1+$r)^t");
$yr3   = $yr2 + random(2, 10);
$c     = $model->eval(t => $yr3 - $year);

BEGIN_PGML
The population of a certain city was [$a] in [$year], and the observed relative
growth rate is [$b] percent per year.

a) Let [`t`] be the number of years after [$year] and [`r`] be the relative growth rate.  Find a function that models the population after [`t`] years.

    [`P(t)=`] [_]{$model}

b) Find the projected population in the year [$yr2]: [_]{$model->eval(t => $diff)}

c) In what year will the population reach [$c]? [_]{$yr3}
END_PGML

$cdiva = Real($c/$a);
$t = ln($cdiva)/ln($rp1);
$t = Real($t);

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
\a. The model will be an exponential model: [`P(t) =  a(1+r)^t`], where the initial population will be [`a=229000`] and growth rate as [`r=[$b]/100 = [$r] `].  The model then is 

    [``` P(t) = [$a]\ast[$rp1]^t ```]
    
\b. To find the projected population, first note that [$yr2] is [`t=[$diff]`] years after [$year]. This value of [`t`] will be substituted into the model so

[``` P([$diff]) = [$a]\ast[$rp1]^{[$diff]} = [$model->eval(t => $diff)] ```]    

\c. Use logarithms to solve the equation 
[``[$c]=[$a]\ast [$rp1]^t ``] for [`t`].

        [``\begin{aligned}
        [$c]&=[$a]\ast [$rp1]^t \\
        [$c]/[$a] &= [$rp1]^t \\
        [$cdiva] &= [$rp1]^t \\
        \ln([$cdiva]) &= \ln\big([$rp1]^t\big)=t \ln([$rp1]) \\
        t &= \frac{\ln([$cdiva])}{\ln([$rp1])}\\
        t &= [$t] \end{aligned}``]

    So the year is [`[$year]+t =[@ $year+$t @]`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

